# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dual-ignition
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:dual-ignition/aero-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:dual-ignition/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Many variations of **aircraft engine starting** have been used since the Wright brothers made their first powered flight in 1903.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The methods used have been designed for weight saving, simplicity of operation and reliability.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Early piston engines were started by hand.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Geared hand starting, electrical and cartridge-operated systems for larger engines were developed between the First and Second World Wars.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine aircraft engines such as turbojets, turboshafts and turbofans often use air/pneumatic starting, with the use of *bleed air* from built-in auxiliary power units (APUs) or external air compressors now seen as a common starting method.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Often only one engine needs be started using the APU (or remote compressor).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] After the first engine is started using APU bleed air, *cross-bleed air* from the running engine can be used to start the remaining engine(s).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Hand starting of aircraft piston engines by swinging the propeller is the oldest and simplest method, the absence of any onboard starting system giving an appreciable weight saving.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Positioning of the propeller relative to the crankshaft is arranged such that the engine pistons pass through top dead centre during the swinging stroke.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] As the ignition system is normally arranged to produce sparks before top dead centre there is a risk of the engine kicking back during hand starting.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] To avoid this problem one of the two magnetos used in a typical aero engine ignition system is fitted with an 'impulse coupling', a spring-loaded device which delays the spark until top dead centre and which also increases the rotational speed of the magneto to produce a stronger spark.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When the engine fires, the impulse coupling no longer operates and the second magneto is switched on.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Note that this is different from the manual "turning over" of a radial piston engine, which is done to release oil that has become trapped in the lower cylinders prior to starting to avoid engine damage.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The two appear similar, but while hand starting involves a sharp, strong "yank" on the prop to start the engine, turning over is simply done by turning the prop through a certain set amount.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Accidents have occurred during lone pilot hand starting, whether due to high throttle settings, brakes not having been applied, or wheel chocks not being used, all resulting in the aircraft moving off without the pilot at the controls.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Hucks starter (invented by Bentfield Hucks during WWI) is a mechanical replacement for the ground crew.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Based on a vehicle chassis the device uses a clutch driven shaft to turn the propeller, disengaging as the engine starts.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] A Hucks starter is used regularly at the Shuttleworth Collection for starting period aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Self-sustaining motor gliders (often known as 'turbos') are fitted with small two-stroke engines with no starting system, for ground testing a cord is wrapped around the propeller boss and pulled rapidly in conjunction with operating decompressor valves.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] These engines are started in flight by operating the decompressor and increasing airspeed to windmill the propeller.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Early variants of the Slingsby Falke motor glider use a cockpit mounted pull start system.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft began to be equipped with electrical systems around 1930, powered by a battery and small wind-driven generator.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The systems were initially not powerful enough to drive starter motors.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of engine-driven generators solved the problem.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Introduction of electric starter motors for aero engines increased convenience at the expense of extra weight and complexity.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] They were a necessity for flying boats with high mounted, inaccessible engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Powered by an onboard battery, ground electrical supply or both, the starter is operated by a key or switch in the cockpit.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The key system usually facilitates switching of the magnetos.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In cold ambient conditions the friction caused by viscous engine oil causes a high load on the starting system.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Another problem is the reluctance of the fuel to vaporise and combust at low temperatures.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Oil dilution systems were developed (mixing fuel with the engine oil), and engine pre-heaters were used (including lighting fires under the engine).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Ki-Gass priming pump system was used to assist starting of British engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Aircraft fitted with variable-pitch propellers or constant speed propellers are started in fine pitch to reduce air loads and current in the starter motor circuit.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Many light aircraft are fitted with a 'starter engaged' warning light in the cockpit, a mandatory airworthiness requirement to guard against the risk of the starter motor failing to disengage from the engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Coffman starter was an explosive cartridge operated device, the burning gases either operating directly in the cylinders to rotate the engine or operating through a geared drive.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] First introduced on the Junkers Jumo 205 diesel engine in 1936 the Coffman starter was not widely used by civil operators due to the expense of the cartridges.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In 1920 Roy Fedden designed a piston engine gas starting system, used on the Bristol Jupiter engine in 1922.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] A system used in early Rolls-Royce Kestrel engines ducted high-pressure air from a ground unit through a camshaft driven distributor to the cylinders via non-return valves, the system had disadvantages only overcome by conversion to electric starting.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When a piston engine needs to be started in flight the electric starter motor can be used.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] This is a normal procedure for motor gliders that have been soaring with the engine turned off.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] During aerobatics with earlier aircraft types it was not uncommon for the engine to cut during manoeuvres due to carburettor design.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] With no electric starter installed, engines can be restarted by diving the aircraft to increase airspeed and the rotation speed of the 'windmilling' propeller.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] An aero engine inertia starter uses a pre-rotated flywheel to transfer kinetic energy to the crankshaft, normally through reduction gears and a clutch to prevent over-torque conditions.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Three variations have been used, hand driven, electrically driven and a combination of both.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] When the flywheel is fully energised either a manual cable is pulled or a solenoid is used to engage the starter.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Starting of a gas turbine engine requires rotation of the compressor to a speed that provides sufficient pressurised air to the combustion chambers.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The starting system has to overcome inertia of the compressor and friction loads, the system remains in operation after combustion starts and is disengaged once the engine has reached self-idling speed.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Two types of electrical starter motor can be used, direct-cranking (to disengage as internal combustion engines) and starter-generator system (permanently engaged).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Small gas turbine engines, particularly turboshaft engines used in helicopters and cruise missile turbojets can be started by a geared hydraulic motor using oil pressure from a ground supply.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] With air-start systems, gas turbine engine compressor spools are rotated by the action of a large volume of compressed air acting directly on the compressor blades or driving the engine through a small, geared turbine motor.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] These motors can weigh up to 75% less than an equivalent electrical system.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The compressed air can be supplied from an on-board auxiliary power unit (APU), a portable gas generator used by ground crew or by cross feeding bleed air from a running engine in the case of multi-engined aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Turbomeca Palouste gas generator was used to start the Spey engines of the Blackburn Buccaneer.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The de Havilland Sea Vixen was equipped with its own Palouste in a removable underwing container to facilitate starting when away from base.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Other military aircraft types using ground supplied compressed air for starting include the Lockheed F-104 Starfighter and variants of the F-4 Phantom using the General Electric J79 turbojet engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Versions of the Rolls-Royce Avon turbojet engine used a geared turbine starter motor that burned isopropyl nitrate as the fuel.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] In military service this monofuel had the NATO designation of S-746 AVPIN.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] For starting a measured amount of fuel was introduced to the starter combustion chamber then ignited electrically, the hot gases spinning the turbine at high revolutions with the exhaust exiting overboard.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Similar in operating principle to the piston engine Coffman starter, an explosive cartridge drives a small turbine engine which is connected by gears to the compressor shaft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Developed for short-haul airliners, most civil and military aircraft requiring self-contained starting systems these units are known by various names including Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), Jet Fuel Starter (JFS), Air Start Unit (ASU) or Gas Turbine Compressor (GTC).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Comprising a small gas turbine which is electrically started, these devices provide compressed bleed air for engine starting and often also provide electrical and hydraulic power for ground operations without the need to run the main engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Two small petrol/oil mix tanks were fitted in the annular intake.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird used two Buick Nailheads as starter motors, which were mounted on an AG-330 Start Kart trolley, later with Chevrolet big-block 454-cubic-inch (7.44 L) V8 engines.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Gas turbine engines can be shut down in flight, intentionally by the crew to save fuel or during a flight test or unintentionally due to fuel starvation or flameout after a compressor stall.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Sufficient airspeed is used to 'windmill' the compressor then fuel and ignition are switched on, an on-board auxiliary power unit may be used at high altitudes where the air density is lower.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] During zoom climb operations of the Lockheed NF-104A the jet engine was shut down on climbing through 85,000 ft (26,000 m) and was started using the windmill method on descent through denser air.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Pulse jet engines are uncommon aircraft powerplants.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] However, the Argus As 014 used to power the V-1 flying bomb and Fieseler Fi 103R Reichenberg was a notable exception.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Once the engine started and the temperature rose to the minimum operating level, the external air hose and connectors were removed, and the resonant design of the tailpipe kept the pulse jet firing.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] Each cycle or pulse of the engine began with the shutters open; fuel was injected behind them and ignited, and the resulting expansion of gases forced the shutters closed.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] As the pressure in the engine dropped following combustion, the shutters reopened and the cycle was repeated, roughly 40 to 45 times per second.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-engine-starting] The electrical ignition system was used only to start the engine; heating of the tailpipe skin maintained combustion.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] An **aircraft fuel system** allows the crew to pump, manage, and deliver aviation fuel to the propulsion system and auxiliary power unit (APU) of an aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel systems differ greatly due to different performance of the aircraft in which they are installed.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A single-engine piston aircraft has a simple fuel system, while a tanker (such as the KC-135) not only manages its own fuel but can also provide fuel to other aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Fuel is piped through fuel lines to a fuel control valve (usually known as the fuel selector).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The first function is to act as a fuel shut-off valve.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This is required to provide the crew with a means to prevent fuel reaching the engine in case of an engine fire.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The second function is to allow the pilot to choose which tank feeds the engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Many aircraft have the left tank and right tank selections available to the pilot.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Some Cessna airplanes feed only from both tanks; and many have the option to feed from left, right, or both tanks.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The reason to have left only and right only options is to allow pilots to balance fuel load to reduce the banking moment.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] In some aircraft, the shut-off function is a different valve located after the fuel selector valve.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Typically, after the selector valve—situated at a low point in the fuel run—there is a gascolator — a fuel filter that can be opened on the ground and drained of fuel impurities denser than petroleum, mainly water and sediment.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Other drainage points are in each tank (often more than one contaminant collection sump per tank) and at the injection pump.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Each tank is vented (or pressurised) to allow air into the tank to take the place of burned fuel; otherwise, the tank would be in negative pressure which would result in engine fuel starvation.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A vent also allows for changes in atmospheric pressure and temperature.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The fuel level indication system in the simplest form is a transparent window on the tank side and in its usual application a float-driven potentiometer installed in the tank.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] After the TWA Flight 800 disaster, a revision was made to aircraft fuel systems to address the potential explosion hazard of electrical components located in the fuel tank.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine piston aircraft fuel level systems moved to utilize float level gauges from the CNG and LPG industries which had the float drive a magnetic coupling and relocated the potentiometer outside the fuel tank.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Some single-engine aircraft use capacitive probes in the fuel tanks.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] As fuel is burned, more air enters the tank and the capacitance decreases; this is read by a computer and the fuel amount is calculated and displayed to the pilots.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Recent advances in magnetoresistive technology have evolved new fuel level sensors for general aviation applications.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This system is not affected by any additive or fuel combination to replace 100LL for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Single-engine light aircraft fuel tanks are usually in the wings, but some aircraft have a small "header tank" between the normal fuel tank and the engine, to facilitate reliable fuel flow to the engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] On many small or very old single-engine aircraft, header tanks (and even main tanks) are often mounted above and/or immediately behind the engine.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A few (particularly ultralight aircraft) have them in the fuselage or on the airframe behind the pilot and/or passenger(s).
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Adding tanks and engines increases the complexity of the fuel system and its management.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] All of the considerations made for the twin piston are applicable to turbine fuel systems.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Additional consideration apply because of the higher altitudes, different fuel, lower temperatures, and longer flights.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] To avoid water condensation or the fuel itself solidifying at low temperatures (−55 °C), fuel tanks have thermometers and heating systems.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Many are pressurized with engine bleed air to keep moist air out and ensure positive pressure feed to the pumps.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] In larger aircraft, fuel tanks also are in the fuselage and their load affects the center of gravity of the aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] This imposes limitations on the amount of fuel carried and the order in which fuel must be used.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Turbine engines burn fuel faster than reciprocating engines do.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Because fuel needs to be injected in to a combustor, the injection system of a turbine aircraft must provide fuel at higher pressure and flow compared to that for a piston engine aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] The refueling system of larger aircraft includes a single positive pressure refueling point from which all tanks can be fueled.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] How much and to which tanks fuel is fed during refueling operations is determined by the controls in the refueling panel, usually installed nearby and accessible to ground crews.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] External tanks are used to extend the range of an aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] Drop tanks are used by combat aircraft that need to discard them after use for performance reasons.
[src:dual-ignition/aircraft-fuel-system] A fuel pump is required to transfer fuel from a tip tank to a main tank.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The **ARV Super2** (*Air Recreational Vehicle*) is a British two-seat light aircraft with strut-braced shoulder wings and tricycle landing gear.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Designed by Bruce Giddings, the Super2 was available either factory-built or as a kit.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] It was intended to be both a cost-effective trainer and an affordable aircraft for private owners.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Later called the "Opus", it gained US FAA Light-Sport Aircraft approval in February 2008.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] About 35 aircraft were produced in the 1980s before the Isle of Wight-based company went into liquidation.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Subsequently, there have been a number of attempts to restart production, all unsuccessful, of which the most recent was by Opus Aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] In November 2013, Opus Aircraft announced that its assets had been auctioned off successfully, adding: "We hope to see our plans continued and to see the all-aluminum plane flying by 2015." Since 2015, little has been heard of the ARV and no resumption of production has occurred.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Noble established a factory at Sandown on the Isle of Wight to build the ARV Super2 aircraft, with the first prototype flying on 11 March 1985.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The factory used some novel manufacturing techniques, including British ALCAN's "Supral" (a superplastic aluminium alloy), adhesives (to reduce the number of rivets and thereby save weight), and a bespoke new British engine, the Hewland AE75.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] These innovations gave the ARV an empty weight 40% lower than the Cessna 152, making the Super2 both cheaper to buy and to operate.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV Super2 is a side-by-side configuration two-seater with a shoulder wing for improved visibility.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The wing is swept forward 5° to maintain correct centre of gravity balance.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The wing area is a small 92 sq ft (8.5 m2), giving a wing loading of 11.9 lb/ft2 (58.1 kg/m2).
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The forward sweep may also promote a spanwise airflow inwards towards the root, thereby reducing the likelihood of a wingtip stall.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV's tapered fibreglass wingtips help to reduce drag from wingtip vortices.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV is constructed mainly of aluminium alloy, with fibreglass wingtips, cowlings and canopy frame.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The cockpit is a stiff monocoque of "Supral" alloy for lightness and improved crash protection.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Aft of the cockpit bulkhead, the ARV is conventionally built, with frames, longerons and a stressed skin forming a semi-monocoque.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Skin sections are both glued and riveted.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Ailerons, elevators and flaps are pushrod-controlled, but the rudder and trim are cable-linked.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Both rudder and elevator are horn-balanced.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The rudder pedals also control a steerable nosewheel, but the hand-operated disc brakes are not differential and do not contribute to steering.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The AE75 engine, a 49 kg (108 lb)75 hp (56 kW) inverted three-cylinder water-cooled two-stroke unit with dual ignition and a 2.7:1 reduction gearbox, was specially developed for the ARV by Hewland from their existing two-cylinder microlight engine.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The AE75 engine has a TBO of only 800 hours, and, in the absence of continuing factory support, many ARVs have had their AE75s replaced with engines such as the Rotax 912, the Rotax 914, or the Jabiru 2200.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Three ARVs were fitted with a MidWest twin-rotor wankel as their original engine.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The Super2 gained airworthiness certification in July 1986, and soon after entered production.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] In November 1985, Noble had reached an agreement to supply ARV parts to Canada's Instar Aviation, where the aircraft was intended to be assembled for the North American market.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Transport Canada had agreed to certify the aircraft based on it "meeting UK criteria", but in the end these Canadian production plans came to nothing.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Originally, ARVs were available either as kit-built aircraft (subject to PFA Permit), or factory built (and subject to the CAA Certificate of Airworthiness).
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] In the spring of 1990 Aviation Scotland Limited was to restart production and in 1993 that company intended to set up another facility in Sweden to build ARVs.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] In the late 1990s the aircraft was sold in kit form in the US as the Highlander by Highlander Aircraft Corporation of Golden Valley, Minnesota.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] In 2004, the CAA reclassified all ARVs as PFA (now LAA) Permit aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV Super2 was originally intended to be aerobatic, but the Isle of Wight factory closed before CAA clearance was obtained, so aerobatics remain prohibited.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Also, the factory had planned to develop a four-seater version, wing-tip tanks and floats.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Opus Aircraft upgraded some specifications for the aircraft, increasing the Vne to 134 kn (248 km/h) and increasing the gross weight to 1,168 lb (530 kg).
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The company intended to equip the aircraft with the Rotax 912UL or 912A of 80 hp (60 kW).
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV Super2 has had an interrupted production history, with a number of successive companies producing 40 aircraft in total.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Shortly after initial aircraft deliveries began, there were a number of forced landings.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] These were due to gearbox failures induced by propeller vibration, and in November 1987 the CAA grounded the aircraft.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Although these problems were quickly resolved, the aircraft's reputation suffered.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Buyers and investors lost confidence, leading to the closure of the Isle of Wight factory and the company was forced into administration.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] This resulted in a management buyout and the company being renamed *Island Aircraft*.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Some 30 or so aircraft were completed by ARV and then by Island Aircraft at Sandown.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Production was then transferred first to Scotland and then to Sweden, where the ARV was renamed the "Opus 280", However, no aircraft were produced in Sweden before the proprietors went bankrupt in 1995.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] After yet another unsuccessful attempt to restart production in Ohio, USA, all manufacturing rights (plus a selection of aircraft parts) were sold to a new consortium, "Opus Aircraft".
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Opus Aircraft established a factory at Rockingham, near Stoneville, North Carolina, and in February 2008, the "Opus Super 2" was granted FAA Light Sport Aircraft approval.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The factory produced an "Opus Super 2" prototype, but the proposed resumption of production never occurred.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The company, valued at US$8 million, was offered for sale for US$2.9 million, and in October 2013 the company was purchased at auction.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV Super2 has received favourable reviews which describe it as an aircraft with excellent visibility that is pleasant to fly.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The small wing area and the fairly high wing loading produces handling that is responsive but stable.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] A drawback for touring is the shortage of luggage space.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The second prototype, G-STWO, has a fuselage luggage compartment aft of the fuel tank which is accessed from the starboard aside, but no other ARVs have this feature.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] After initial production commenced at least two flying schools adopted the ARV, but today most Super2s in the UK are flown privately.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The Hewland AE75 engine, which is no longer available, has a life of 800 hours, after which time alternative engines must be installed.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Replacement engines have all been heavier than the 49 kg (108 lb) original, needing a lead counterweight in the tail to maintain balance.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The empenage is short-coupled and its area is a little marginal for the landing flare, so flaring with a stopped engine (and thus no propwash) might prove problematic.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] LAA-approved modifications include ground-adjustable propellers, tundra tyres, additional fuel tanks and fuel-injection.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The LAA has approved the fitting and testing of vortex generators, with a view to reducing stall speed and improving landing flare.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The perspex canopy, which gives sailplane-like visibilty, is hinged at the rear.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] To open the canopy, one rotates it up and back.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The canopy is secured at the front by two over-centre catches operated from outside and within the cockpit.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Even in the early days of the ARV, this was considered a design weakness, since if a catch fails or is not properly engaged, the canopy could flip up and cause massive drag.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Such an incident actually happened in 2025 when the canopy flipped open shortly after take-off.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] The ARV crash-landed in a field; the pilot was OK but the aircraft was a write-off.
[src:dual-ignition/arv-super2] Some ARV owners have, (with LAA approval), converted their canopies to have a hinge at the forward end and catches at the rear, so that if the catches fail, the canopy will not flip wide open.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Dual ignition provides two advantages: redundancy in the event of in-flight failure of one ignition system; and more efficient burning of the fuel-air mixture within the combustion chamber.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] In aircraft and gasoline-powered fire fighting equipment, redundancy is the prime consideration, but in other vehicles the main targets are efficient combustion and meeting emission law requirements.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] A dual ignition system will typically provide that each cylinder has twin spark plugs, and that the engine will have at least two ignition circuits, such as duplicate magnetos or ignition coils.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Dual ignition promotes engine efficiency by initiating twin flame fronts, giving faster and more complete burning and thereby increasing power.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] The Nash Ambassador for 1932-1948 used twin sparkplugs on the straight eight engine, while later Alfa Romeo Twin Spark cars use dual ignition, as do Honda cars with the i-DSI series engines, and Chrysler's Modern Hemi engine.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] In 1980 Nissan installed twin sparkplugs on the Nissan NAPS-Z engine, with Ford introducing it on the 1989 Ford Ranger and 1991 Ford Mustang four-cylinder models.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Several modern Mercedes-Benz engines also have two spark plugs per cylinder, such as the M112 and M113 engines.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Some motorcycles, such as the Honda VT500 and the Ducati Multistrada, also have dual ignition.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] The 2012 Ducati Multistrada was upgraded with "twin-plug cylinder heads for smoother, more efficient combustion", the change contributing to a 5% increase in torque and a 10% improvement in fuel consumption.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Early BMW R1100S bikes had a single spark plug per cylinder, but after 2003 they were upgraded to dual ignition to meet emission law requirements.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Dual ignition in aero-engines should enable the aircraft to continue to fly safely after an ignition system failure.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Operation of aero engines on one magneto (rather than both) typically results in an rpm drop of around 75 rpm.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Its existence on aviation powerplants dates back to the World War I years, when such engines as the Hispano-Suiza 8 and Mercedes D.III, and even rotary engines as the later Gnome Monosoupape model 9N 160 hp (119 kW) versions featured twin spark plugs per cylinder.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] The Hewland AE75, an inline three cylinder aero-engine created for the ARV Super2, had three ignition circuits, each circuit serving a plug in two different cylinders.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] If just one of the three circuits failed, all three cylinders still received sparks, and even if two circuits were to fail, the remaining circuit would keep the engine running on two cylinders.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] While true dual ignition uses completely separate and redundant systems, some certified engines, such as the Lycoming O-320-H2AD use a single engine magneto drive-shaft turning two separate magnetos.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Whilst saving weight, this creates a single point of failure in mechanical terms, that could cause both ignition systems to cease working.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] A simple form of partial dual ignition on some amateur-built aircraft uses a single spark plug, but duplicates the coil and pick-up for better redundancy than traditional single ignition.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] A further form of partial dual ignition (such as on the Honda VT500) is for each cylinder to have a single HT coil which sends the current to one plug and completes the circuit via the second plug, rather than via the earth.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] This system requires a voltage sufficient to jump both plug gaps, but an advantage is that if one plug fouls, the fouled plug may burn itself clean while the engine continues running.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Wankel engines have such an elongated combustion chamber that even non-aero wankel engines may adopt dual ignition to promote better combustion.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] The MidWest AE series Wankel aero-engine has twin plugs per chamber, but these are placed side-by-side, not sequentially, so their main purpose is to give redundancy rather than improved combustion.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Dilworth of the Electo-Motive Corporation devised a system, using four spark plugs and one carburettor per cylinder, in order to burn "distillate" fuel in train car engines.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] Because such heavy, but cheap, fuel was hard to ignite, a quadruple system of ignition was used in order to burn fuel roughly equivalent to kerosene or home heating fuel.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] By using this distillate fuel, that cost as little as one-fifth the price of gasoline before the Great Depression, a railroad could save substantially on fuel costs.
[src:dual-ignition/dual-ignition] However, this patented ignition system saw little commercial use.
